	<refnamediv>
		<refname>berc_get_errors</refname>

		<refpurpose>BERC get errors</refpurpose>
	</refnamediv>

	<refsynopsisdiv>
		<title>Calling Sequence</title>

		<synopsis> a = berc_get_errors(b,c)</synopsis>
	</refsynopsisdiv>
	
	<refsection>

		<title>Parameters</title>

		<variablelist>                                                                            
			<varlistentry><term>a:</term>
				<listitem><para> output number of bit errors in input bitstreams.</para></listitem></varlistentry>      
                         <varlistentry><term>b:</term>        
				<listitem><para> input binary array of {0,1}.</para></listitem></varlistentry>   
			<varlistentry><term>c:</term>        
				<listitem><para> input binary array of {0,1}.</para></listitem></varlistentry>        
		</variablelist>

	</refsection>



	<refsection>
		<title>Description</title>

		<para>BERC get errors </para>
	
		<para>The function gives the number of bit errors in the two input bitstreams.</para>

		<para>It is expected that the user inputs two binary arrays of (0,1) in scilab engine while calling the berc_get_errors() and expect the function to return the error count of the two bitstreams as output in scilab console.
		</para>
		
	</refsection>

	<refsection>
		<title>Examples</title>

		<programlisting role="example">b=[1 0 0 1 1 0];&#10;c=[1 1 0 0 1 1];&#10;a=berc_get_errors(b,c)</programlisting>
	</refsection>

	<refsection>
		<title>Authors</title>

